4/28/2026

Set up pfSense and created a segmented network with LAN and DMZ

Installed pfSense in VMware and assigned interfaces:

WAN (NAT)
LAN (VMnet1, 192.168.10.0/24)
DMZ (OPT1, VMnet2, 192.168.2.0/24)

Connected machines:
Kali (LAN)
Ubuntu (DMZ)
Wazuh VM (LAN)

Initially trying to get communication working between the machines

Problem:
Kali could not ping anything at first

Troubleshooting:
Ran:
ip a
Saw IP was assigned correctly

Ran:
ip route
Noticed there was no default gateway, which means it could not reach the internet

Added gateway:
ip route add default via 192.168.10.1

After that, pinging started working

Then moved on to testing communication from the Ubuntu machine in the DMZ

Problem:
Ubuntu could not reach other systems or communicate as expected

From Ubuntu:
ping 192.168.2.1 (pfSense DMZ gateway)

Had  no response

Started troubleshooting on Ubuntu

Checked IP configuration:
ip a
IP was assigned correctly (192.168.2.x)

Checked routing:
ip route
Verified default route existed

Still no communication

Began trying to fix network configuration on Ubuntu

Looked into network config files under /etc/netplan and /etc/network

Made changes and reapplied configs:
sudo netplan apply

Also restarted networking multiple times

After changes, still no improvement

At this point confirmed:
IP was correct
routing was correct
interface was up

So issue likely not on Ubuntu side

Shifted focus to pfSense firewall

Checked firewall rules again

Realized my "allow dmz outbound" rule source was set to OPT1 address instead of OPT1 subnet

Tried pinging again from Ubuntu machine after implementing FW change
Worked!

Also configured "block dmz to lan" and "allow dmz ping firewall" (in case ICMP was blocking pings)
see dmz-firewall-rules.png in screenshots

Confirmed DMZ was blocked from lan:
From Ubuntu:
ping 192.168.10.x
No response, rule works

Ran into another issue

Problem:
Kali could not ping pfSense LAN gateway anymore (192.168.10.1)
100% packet loss when trying to ping

Troubleshooting:

Checked IP:
ip a
IP still correct

Checked route:
ip route
Gateway still set

Tried ping again (still failing)

Checked ARP:
ip neigh
Saw:
192.168.10.1 REACHABLE

So Layer 2 is working

Tried disabling firewall on pfSense:
pfctl -d

No change

Conclusion:
Not a firewall issue

Restarted pfSense

After reboot:
ping 192.168.10.1 
Worked again

Noticed a pattern:
pfSense stops working when starting or rebooting a VM on the network

Workaround/Temporary fix:
Restart pfSense when this happens
Will look into permanent fix soon

Also started setting static IPs to avoid DHCP issues

Began setting up Wazuh

Created new Ubuntu VM on LAN

Installed Wazuh using installer script

Got warning about UFW blocking ports

Disabled UFW temporarily:
sudo ufw disable

Finished install

Verified:
(Wazuh dashboard accessible at https://192.168.10.x)

What I learned:
How to do basic network segmenting
Default gateway is required for communication outside local network
Difference between having an IP and having a route
ARP showing REACHABLE means Layer 2 works but does not guarantee communication
Basic router firewall configuration
Using subnet vs interface address matters when creating rules
How to test network behavior step by step:
ip a
ip route
ping
ip neigh
pfSense can stop responding when new VMs connect and may require a reboot
Static IPs help avoid DHCP issues and inconsistent behavior in a lab environment
Basic understanding of how SIEM (Wazuh) fits into a network

Was really cool to see so much of what I learned in Network+ in action
